1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {The e3 Nimzo is back at the top level.
Earlier it was trending at some point when Ivan Sokolov managed to defeat
Kasparov in 1999!} O-O {We almost always reply with Bd2, with very few
exceptions.} (4... Bxc3+ $6 {I have focused on studying two games played by
Rubinstein decades ago!}) (4... b6 {is also playable.}) (4... c5 {Only this
line is independent, as White now cannot play the routine Bd2, which allows
Black to equalise comfortably by entering a favourable IQP position after cd
followed by d5.} 5. Nge2 {is our choice.}) (4... d5 5. Bd2 {Sooner or later,
play transposes to one of the lines we study.}) 5. Bd2 $5 {This move caught my
attention when a fellow GM and good friend of mine, Sandipan Chanda, kept
playing it with exceptional results. I always felt that it is difficult to
have a fixed and narrow repertoire these days since technology has improved a
lot and it is easier to navigate through opponents' games and prepare
something new just a few hours before the game. I was curious about this fact
and wondering how he manages to score well in this line, so I started studying
his games, though I rarely play 1.d4 these days. Then I realised that this
line is mainly about middlegame understanding. I even suggested some of my
students employ it before deciding to write an article on this subject.} d5 ({
The popular alternative} 5... b6 {is also possible.}) 6. Nf3 b6 (6... c5 7. a3)
7. cxd5 exd5 {Here I have focused on three different lines with minor nuances
between them.} 8. Rc1 {is our Plan A,} (8. Bd3 {is our Plan B, with the idea
to play Qb1 followed by b4, a4 etc.}) 8... a6 {Black has to commit to this at
some point, to stop White from playing Nb5. Again we see two different
approaches by White.} 9. Bd3 {Naturally, our plan A.} (9. Be2 {Our plan B.}) *

