[EventRounds "11"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {Sandipan has played many games in this
line. I would suggest my dear readers study them for better middlegame
understanding.} O-O 5. Bd2 {This will be the subject of our article.} d5 6. Nf3
b6 7. cxd5 {The typical move whenever Black plays b6.} exd5 8. Rc1 {A useful
move to include before developing our kingside pieces.} a6 {Black has to play
this move at some point to prevent White from playing Nb5. The exchange of the
dark-squared bishops is favourable for White in such structures, since his
light-squared bishop is stronger than its counterpart.} 9. Be2 $5 {With a deep
idea! White can play Ne4 at some point so that when black captures de4, our
light-squared bishop won't come under attack, as it stands on e2 instead of d3.
} (9. Bd3 {is our main focus in this article.}) 9... Bb7 10. O-O Nbd7 {Black's
idea in such positions is to launch an attack on White's kingside by playing
Bd6, Qe7, Ne4 etc. So it makes sense for White to exchange some of Black's
minor pieces.} 11. Ne5 Qe7 (11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. Nxd5 Bxd2 14. Qxd2 Nxe5
15. Rfd1 $14) 12. Nxd7 Nxd7 13. Qb3 Nf6 14. Ne4 $1 {The point of White's 9th
move!} Bxd2 15. Nxd2 $14 {White already has won the opening battle, as this is
a dream position for him after 1.d4, especially in the Nimzo. White's minor
pieces are stronger than his counterpart's. He has control over the c-file.
Black is doomed to passivity due to his weak queenside pawns. If White manages
to exchange queens, play becomes very difficult for black.} Qd6 16. Qc3 (16.
Rc3 {[%cal Gf1c1,Gb3a3] Doubling rooks on the c-file makes more sense as White
also intends to play Qa3 to exchange queens.}) 16... Rfc8 17. b4 {
Strengthening control over the dark squares.} a5 18. b5 c5 (18... c6 {was
probably better.}) 19. Qa3 $1 Qf8 20. dxc5 bxc5 $16 {[%csl Gb5] Now White has
a passed b-pawn and Black still hasn't solved his queenside problems. Play
becomes easier for White.} 21. Bf3 $1 {[%csl Rc5,Rd5][%cal Gf3a8] , and White
won convincingly: 1-0 (72) Sandipan,C (2545)-Lalith, B (2556) Majitar IND 2019}
*

