1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd2 d5 6. Nf3 b6 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Bd3
{Here White develops the bishop to d3 instead of e2} Bb7 9. O-O {In the
previous game we saw White develop his queenside before his kingside by
playing Rc1 first. Here White has another idea in mind.} Bd6 (9... Nbd7 {
is also possible.}) 10. Qb1 $5 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gd3h7,Gf3e5] The move which was
also played by Alpha Zero. White not only keeps an eye on the b1-h7 diagonal
but also intends to expand on the queenside by playing b4.} Re8 (10... a5 {
was played by Stockfish. It probably "thought" Black's position would start
collapsing if White expands on the queenside. On the downside, the b5 square
is seriously weakened and whenever black plays c6 to control it, the bishop on
b7 will be passive.} 11. Nb5 Be7 12. h3 g6 13. Nc3 {1/2-1/2 (131)
AlphaZero-Stockfish 8 London ENG 2018}) 11. b4 a6 12. Rc1 {Black is behind in
development whereas White has focused his major pieces on the queenside.
Another plus of playing Rfc1 is that White vacates the f1-square for the king
just in case Black manages to launch an attack on White's king.} ({Sandipan
deviated from his game played a few weeks ago by playing} 12. b5 $5 axb5 13.
Nxb5 Bf8 14. Ng5 {White goes into tactical mode now!} g6 15. f4 $1 {A typical
attacking move.} Nbd7 16. f5 Bh6 17. e4 $18 Nxe4 18. fxg6 Nxd2 19. gxf7+ Kg7
20. Nxc7 Qxc7 21. fxe8=N+ Rxe8 22. Rf7+ Kh8 23. Qd1 Bg7 24. Qh5 Bxd4+ 25. Kh1
Nf6 26. Rxf6 Qe7 27. Nf7+ {1-0 (27) Sandipan, C (2545)-Mohammad Fahad, R (2294)
Mumbai IND 2020}) 12... Nbd7 13. a4 Nf8 $6 {Too slow.} ({Black should have
tried to play for an attack, starting with} 13... Ne4 {[%cal Gg7g5]}) 14. b5 a5
{[%csl Ga4,Ra5,Gb5,Rb6] This structure is generally favourable for White, as
the c7-pawn remains a permanent weakness, and if Black manages to play c7-c6,
the b6-pawn and the b5-square become a weakness after bc6.} 15. Rc2 $1 {
[%cal Gd2c1,Gc1a3] A typical idea in such positions, as Black's bishop on d6
not only controls the b8-h2 diagonal but also defends the important c7-pawn.}
Ne4 16. Bc1 g5 17. Ba3 {White is just on time to eliminate the important
dark-squared bishop.} g4 18. Bxd6 cxd6 {[%csl Gd5,Gd6] This way of recapture
was advocated by Iron Tigran Petrosian, and he often successfully defended
such passive positions.} 19. Bxe4 {White tries to remove as much of Black's
attacking potential as possible, striving for a technical position.} dxe4 20.
Nd2 d5 21. Qd1 $1 $16 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gc3e2,Ge2f4,Gd2f1] Black's light-squared
bishop is out of the game forever, thanks to White's a4- and b5-pawns. White
won a great technical game in Sandipan, C (2545)-Vaibhav, S (2597) Majitar IND
2019} *

