1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd2 b6 6. Nf3 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Rc1
Be7 {Here Black decides to keep his bishop on e7 instead of d6, so that it
won't come under attack after White's Nb5.} 9. Bd3 Bb7 10. O-O c5 11. Ne5 {
White's typical move in this variation.} Nc6 {Logical play from both sides so
far.} (11... Nbd7 {is also possible. Now White can make use of the fact that
the d4-pawn is not attacked by the knight by playing} 12. f4) 12. Ne2 $5 Rc8 (
12... Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd7 (13... Ne4 {was probably better than the text.}) 14. f4
) 13. Ng3 cxd4 $6 {From here Black gradually went downhill.} (13... g6 $1 {
Maintaining the tension in the centre and stopping White from playing Ng3-f5
was probably a better way to handle this position.}) 14. Nxc6 Rxc6 15. exd4 {
Though the position looks innocuous, in practice it is very difficult to hold.}
Rxc1 16. Bxc1 $1 {White keeps the option of moving the Queen to a4 or f3,
based on how Black responds.} Ne4 17. Qa4 $1 Qc7 18. Be3 {White is playing
logically and at the same time creating small threats to maintain the pressure.
} Bd6 19. Rc1 Qb8 20. Ba6 $1 {A difficult move to play because White's bishop
stands better than its counterpart. However, if we take a deeper look, Black's
light-squared bishop is holding the queenside together. White can penetrate on
the weak c6-square only after exchanging it.} g6 $6 {We will see how this
logical pawn push proved expensive for Black.} (20... h6 {was also fine.}) (
20... Rd8 {was preferable.}) 21. Bxb7 Qxb7 22. Qc6 $1 Qxc6 23. Rxc6 Nxg3 (23...
Bxg3 24. hxg3 {[%csl Ge3,Re4] The position is open and the knight doesn't have
any outposts. White is clearly on top here as well.}) 24. hxg3 $1 {A dream
position for White in this structure. Black's two pawn moves (...b6 and ...g6)
proved fatal, as the c6 and h6 squares were weakened.} (24. Rxd6 $6 Nf5 25.
Rxd5 Nxe3 26. fxe3 Rc8 {, with drawing chances for Black.}) 24... Bb8 (24...
Rd8 25. Bg5 Rd7 26. Bf6 $16 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Rc6c8]}) 25. Bh6 Re8 26. a4 $1 {
Another important idea in these positions. White plays on both sides of the
board to create weaknesses.} f5 27. Rf6 $1 {Preventing Black from improving
his king. Black has to spend a few tempi to kick the rook from the f6 square,
meanwhile White can focus on improving his king by bringing it towards the
centre.} Rd8 28. Kf1 (28. b4 {[%csl Ra7,Rb6][%cal Gb4b5] , intending b5, to
fix the pawns on a7 and b6, was also possible.}) 28... Bd6 29. Ke2 Be7 (29...
Re8+ 30. Kd3 Be7 31. Rc6 g5 32. f4 {Black's position is still difficult to
handle.}) 30. Rc6 Bd6 31. Bg5 Rd7 32. Bf6 $1 {Black's pieces are tied down to
passivity and unfortunately, he could not do more than sit and watch White
execute his plan.} Kf7 33. Be5 $18 Ke7 34. f4 Rd8 35. Kf3 h5 36. Ke3 Rd7 37.
Kd3 Rd8 38. Kc3 Ke6 39. a5 bxa5 40. Kb3 Ke7 41. Bxd6+ Rxd6 42. Rxd6 Kxd6 43.
Ka4 {Fedoseev-Ganguly 1-0 2019} *

