1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd2 d5 6. Nf3 b6 7. Rc1 Bb7 8. cxd5
exd5 9. Bd3 Be7 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Ne5 {Now Black starts playing concrete chess.}
Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. f4 Nc5 14. Bb1 d4 {This was the point of black's 11th
move.} 15. Nb5 d3 {Black managed to block White's light-squared bishop to
reduce his attacking potential. However, this game shows that White has enough
resources to create attacking chances.} (15... dxe3 16. Bxe3 $36 {[%cal Gb1h7,
Gc1c8]}) 16. Nd4 a5 17. Qg4 g6 {From now on White's play becomes very concrete.
It is already difficult to suggest a good and sound defense for Black.} 18. f5
Ne4 (18... Qd5 19. f6 h5 (19... Bd8 20. Rxc5 $1 bxc5 21. Nf3 $18 {[%csl Gf3]
[%cal Gg4f4,Gf4h6,Gg4h4,Gh4h6,Ra8h1] For example, if} Qe4 22. Qg5 Kh8 23. Bxd3
$1 Qxd3 24. Qh6 Rg8 25. Ng5 {[%cal Rh6h7]}) 20. Qh3 Bd8 21. Rf5 $1 $40 Ne4 (
21... Qxg2+ 22. Qxg2 Bxg2 23. Kxg2 $1 gxf5 24. Rf1 $1 $36 {[%cal Gf1f5,Gf5h5]
Despite the reduced material, White still holds a dangerous initiative.}) 22.
Bxd3 $1 Nxd2 23. e6 $1 Qxg2+ (23... Qd6 24. Rxh5 gxh5 25. Qxh5 $18) 24. Qxg2
Bxg2 25. Rf2 $36) 19. Bxd3 $1 {Every move becomes obvious when we just sit in
front of the computer and press space. Such calculations are difficult to do
during the game. Apart from openings, we must consistently work on raw and
complex blindfold calculations to improve our visualisation/imagination.} Nxd2
20. fxg6 fxg6 21. Bxg6 Kh8 22. Bxh7 Rxf1+ 23. Rxf1 {I guess this position is
what White had in mind when playing his 18th move. There is no immediate
threat or forced mate here. White is winning for sure, but there is no forced
sequence yet. If we divide the board in two halves, we see that all the white
pieces are directed towards the black king. On the other hand, Black hardly
has any pieces to defend. This factor probably convinced White that there
should be a win somewhere.} Bg5 (23... Nxf1 24. Qh5 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5,Gh5,Gh7] ,
with mate to follow.}) (23... Qd5 24. Rf2 $1 {[%cal Gf2g2]} (24. Bg6 {[%cal
Rg4h5,Rg4h3]} Qxg2+ 25. Qxg2 Bxg2 26. Rf7 $1 $18 {[%cal Rf7h7,Rf7e7,Rg1g2]})
24... Kxh7 25. Qh5+ Kg8 26. Qg6+ Kh8 27. Ne6 $1 $18) 24. Nf5 $1 Qd3 25. Re1 $1
Bxe3+ 26. Kh1 Bh6 27. Qg6 $6 {White slipped after playing beautifully until
now.} (27. Bg6 $1 {[%cal Rf5h6] was the best way to win the game.} Rg8 28. Qh5
$1 Bxg2+ 29. Kxg2 Rxg6+ 30. Qxg6 Qf3+ 31. Kg1 {White's king is very safe here.}
) 27... Bxg2+ $1 28. Kxg2 $2 (28. Qxg2 Kxh7 29. Nxh6 Nf3 30. Rc1 {The engine
claims that White is still pushing in this wild position.}) 28... Qd5+ $2 {
The final blunder.} (28... Qf3+ $1 29. Kg1 Qf4 {[%cal Rd2f3,Yf4h6] , and Black
holds the game.}) 29. Kh3 Qd3+ 30. Kh4 {Najer-Anand 2019 1-0} *

