1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 b6 (4... Bxc3+ $6 {A premature capture. If
Black wants to do this, he should wait until White's commits to a2-a3, so that
the b3-square is weakened. This weakening can later be exploited by placing
the knight on a5, attacking c4 and keeping an eye on the b3-square.
Nonetheless, this idea has a serious drawback, since White's dark-squared
bishop along with the other pieces can wreak havoc on Black's kingside.} 5.
bxc3 {White's idea is to play Bd3, Ne2 followed by f3, e4. Whatever openings
we play, I believe it is a good idea to study old games in those variations.
For this reason, I present a couple of Rubinstein's games.} b6 (5... d6 6. Bd3
O-O 7. e4 e5 8. Ne2 {The knight is better placed here since White keeps the
option of playing f4 at the right moment.} Re8 9. f3 b6 10. O-O Nc6 11. Be3 Ba6
12. Ng3 Na5 {Both sides have played logically so far.} 13. Qe2 c5 14. d5 $1 {
Closing the centre is the best way to focus on the kingside attack, as Black
needs more time to organise counterplay against the c4-pawn.} Kh8 {Time to
open the position!} 15. f4 $1 Nd7 (15... exf4 16. Bxf4 $40 {[%cal Gf4g5,Gg3f5,
Rf1f8]}) 16. f5 {[%cal Gg3h5,Gf1f3,Gf3h3]} f6 17. Nh5 Re7 18. g4 Qe8 19. g5 {
A minor slip by a world-class player.} (19. h4 $18 {[%cal Gf1f2]}) 19... Bxc4
20. Bxc4 Nxc4 21. gxf6 (21. Bc1 $36) 21... gxf6 (21... Nxe3 $1) 22. Bh6 Nb2 23.
Kh1 Nd3 24. Ng7 Rxg7 25. Bxg7+ Kxg7 26. Rg1+ Kh8 27. Qxd3 Qf7 28. Rg3 {White
won comfortably in 1-0 (41) Rubinstein,A-Colle,E Liege 1930}) 6. Bd3 Bb7 7. f3
O-O 8. Ne2 d6 9. e4 {[%csl Rb7,Ge4,Gf3]} Nbd7 10. O-O c5 11. Be3 Rc8 12. Ng3
Rc7 13. Qe2 Qc8 {Logical play from both sides until now.} 14. f4 $1 Ba6 15.
Rac1 Ne8 16. e5 f5 $1 {A typical defensive move.} 17. Rfd1 $6 ({White should
have played the more energetical} 17. d5 $16) 17... cxd4 18. cxd4 dxe5 19. dxe5
Nc5 20. Bc2 Nb7 21. Ba4 {Black now lost his concentration and blundered by
playing} Bxc4 $4 22. Rxc4 Rxc4 23. Bd7 $1 {1-0 (23) Rubinstein,A-Winter,W
Scarborough/ North Yorkshire 1930}) (4... d6 {Another approach from Black to
deviate from mainstream theory. However, this move has its drawback as it
shuts down the a3-f8 diagonal and more or less forces black to capture on c3
after White plays a2-a3.} 5. Nge2 $1 {Here this is better, to be able to
recapture on c3 with the knight.} c5 ({As usual we will study some of the
classics in this line!} 5... O-O 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. Nxc3 {White already has a
better position due to the bishop pair.} e5 8. Be2 Qe7 9. O-O Bf5 $6 10. f3 $1
Nc6 11. Nd5 $1 Nxd5 12. cxd5 Nb8 13. e4 Bc8 14. Be3 $16 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Ga1c1,
Gd1c2] 1-0 (46) Euwe,M-Yanofsky,D Groningen 1946}) 6. dxc5 dxc5 7. Qxd8+ {
It is no surprise when an endgame virtuoso like Smyslov trades queens this
early in the game.} Kxd8 8. Bd2 Ke7 9. Nf4 $1 {Since the position is open, it
makes sense for White to recapture on c3 with the bishop.} b6 10. a3 Ba5 {
This position has been used for tactical training in many books, including the
famous 'Woodpecker method'.} (10... Bxc3 11. Bxc3 $14 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Gc3h8,
Gf2f3,Ge3e4]}) 11. b4 $1 cxb4 12. axb4 Bxb4 13. Ncd5+ Nxd5 14. Nxd5+ exd5 15.
Bxb4+ Kf6 16. cxd5 $16 {1-0 (46) Smyslov,V-Stoltz,G Bucharest 1953 MCL 
[Smyslov,V]}) (4... Nc6 {This is the kind of move that Black players opt for
to take White out of their theoretical zone. One of the key ideas is to play
d6, e5 or an immediate e5.} 5. Bd2 {We stick to our routine move!} O-O (5... d5
6. Nf3 O-O 7. a3 Bxc3 8. Bxc3 Ne4 9. Rc1 Qe7 10. Bd3 Nxc3 11. Rxc3 e5 12. Nxe5
Nxe5 13. dxe5 dxc4 14. Rxc4 g6 15. Qc2 c6 16. f4 $16 {1-0 (49) Zvjaginsev,V 
(2610)-Blatny,P (2540) NY Open, New York USA 1997}) 6. Bd3 d6 (6... e5 $146 7.
d5 Ne7 8. Nge2 c6 9. e4 d6 10. O-O {, with a lively game where White is on top.
}) 7. Nge2 e5 8. d5 Ne7 9. a3 Ba5 10. b4 Bb6 11. Na4 $14 {[%cal Ra4b6] 1-0 (33)
Petkov,V (2490) -Pantev,V (2369) Plovdiv BUL 2010}) 5. Bd2 {As usual we stick
to our move.} Bb7 6. Nf3 Bxc3 (6... d5 $4 7. Qa4+ Nc6 8. cxd5 Bxc3 (8... exd5
9. Bb5 $18 {[%cal Ra4e8,Gf3e5]}) 9. dxc6 Bxd2+ 10. Nxd2 $18) (6... O-O {
transposes to chapter 10.}) (6... c5 7. a3 {A typical move whenever Black
plays c5.} Bxc3 (7... Ba5 $6 8. b4 $1 {Black should always watch out for b4
whenever he plays Ba5.} cxb4 9. Nb5 Bxf3 10. gxf3 (10. Qxf3 Nc6 $11 {1/2-1/2 
(35) Tsakiris,H (2264) -Pavlidis,A (2529) Kavala GRE 2015}) 10... bxa3 (10...
Nc6 11. d5 exd5 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Bc4 $18) 11. Bxa5 bxa5 12. Nd6+ Ke7 13. c5
$36 {[%csl Re7]}) 8. Bxc3 Ne4 9. Rc1 O-O 10. Bd3 cxd4 $2 11. Bxe4 Bxe4 12. Qxd4
$18 {[%cal Rd4g7,Rd4e4] 1-0 (12) Bartel,M (2612)-Matuszewski,M (2518) Katowice
POL 2019}) 7. Bxc3 Ne4 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gf7f5,Ga8h1] This is the point behind
Black's last move. He now tries to imbalance the position by playing Ne4, f5
and if possible Rf6-Rh6 etc.} 8. Bb4 {White is desperate to maintain the
bishop pair.} (8. Rc1 Nxc3 9. Rxc3 d6 $11 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge6e5,Gd7f6]}) 8... d6 (
8... c5 9. Ba3 O-O 10. Be2 d6 11. O-O Nd7 12. Nd2 $146 {In general White
should try to eliminate the black knight on e4 as soon as possible.} (12. Rc1
f5 13. b4 Qe7 14. Qd3 e5 15. bxc5 bxc5 16. dxe5 dxe5 $13 {1-0 (37) Maghsoodloo,
