Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd2 d5 6. Nf3 b6 7. cxd5 {Typical move
whenever Black plays b6} exd5 8. Rc1 {[%cal Gc3b5] White develops the
queenside pieces first. Here White's main objective is to exchange the
dark-squared bishop, which would help his play on the queenside.} a6 {One of
the key ideas for Black is to place the bishop on d6, so that it not only
defends the queenside, but also keeps an eye on the b8-h2 diagonal and helps
create attacking chances.} 9. Bd3 (9. Be2 $5 {Analysed in Model game 1.}) 9...
Bb7 10. O-O {In this chapter we shall deal with Bd6 ideas. White's key ideas
are as follows: 1. Play Ne5 followed by f4 and Qf3. Control of the e4-square
is important. White later has the option to play Qh3.2. After playing f2-f4,
White must always look for an opportunity to improve his bad bishop with
Be1-h4.3. Intermediate moves like Bf5 should always be considered whenever
White's knight is on e5 4. The knight on c3 can sometimes join the kingside
attack by the route Nc3-e2-g3-f5/h5 or join the queenside attack by Nc3-a4 5.
Sometimes it will be necessary to play a silent move like Rcd1, not only to
defend the d4-pawn but also to keep an eye on the knight on d7-knight and the
queen on d8.} Bd6 {In this chapter we shall deal with Bd6 ideas.} (10... Nbd7 {
The ideas in this variation are similar to the Colle system. White wants to
play f4 and then Qf3, to stop Black from playing Ne4.} 11. Ne5 Bd6 (11... Nxe5
{In general this move is favourable for White since the attack becomes easier
for him.} 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. f4 Nc5 {White has more than one way to gain a
decisive advantage.} (13... Re8 14. Bb1 Nf8 15. a3 Be7 16. Ne2 c5 17. Ng3 $40 {
[%cal Yg3f5,Yg3h5] 0-1 (42) Lalith,B (2580)-Morawietz,D (2405) Biel SUI 2019})
(13... Be7 14. Qh5 {It is useful to provoke Black to play g6, which would be a
