[%cal Gc3b2,Rc3h8,Ge1c1] Though we reached an ending with opposite-coloured
bishops, our bishop on c3 is doing a fantastic job, defending the b2-pawn and
keeping an eye on Black's kingside. Black has to be precise to hold the
balance.}) 12. bxc3 bxc5 13. c4 $1 {[%csl Rc5]} Qa5+ (13... Bb7 $2 14. Bxh7+ $1
Kxh7 15. Qb1+ $18 {[%cal Rb1h7,Rb1b7]}) (13... dxc4 $2 14. Be4 $18 {[%csl Ge4]
[%cal Re4a8]}) (13... g6 14. O-O Bb7 15. Rb1 $16) 14. Qd2 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 $14 {
, with a very pleasant ending for White due to the weak c5-pawn and the
undeveloped black queenside.}) 11. Bc2 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4h5,Gh5g6]} 12. Qb1 $5 {
[%cal Gf3e5] Removing our queen from the pin.} Bxf3 (12... Nbd7 13. Ne5 $16) (
12... Bh5 13. Ne5 Bg6 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. b3 $14) 13. gxf3 {Though our structure
is shattered, White's king is very safe and he can use the open g-file to
organise an attack. Though the engine claims Black is better, I find this
easier to play for White, as he can constantly keep creating problems for
Black.} Nc6 {Here White chose a different yet interesting approach.} (13... Re8
14. O-O Nc6 15. Kh1 Qc7 (15... b5 {was the best way to play.} 16. Rg1 a5 17.
Qf1 b4 18. Bd2 {[%cal Gc2a4,Gf1g2] , and now Black doesn't have any target to
attack. On the other hand, White's position is easy to play.}) 16. Rg1 Ne7 17.
Qf1 $1 Ng6 {At first it looks like Black's kingside is safe. However, it was
not meant to be, as White has f3-f4.} 18. Qg2 $18 {[%cal Gf3f4,Gf4f5] 1-0 (38)
Karthik,V (2462) -Kubicka,A (2241) Suwalki POL 2019}) 14. Ba4 $5 {Slowing down
Black's counterplay on the queenside.} (14. O-O {was still possible.} b5 15.
Kh1 a5 16. Rg1 b4 17. Bd2 {[%cal Gb1f1,Gf1g2]}) 14... Ne7 15. Rg1 a5 16. Ke2
Rb8 17. Qe1 {[%cal Re1a5]} Qd6 (17... b5 18. Bxa5) 18. Bc2 Rfe8 19. Qf1 Ng6 20.
Kd2 Qxh2 $6 (20... Ne7 {[%cal Gg7g6] should be preferred.} 21. Qg2 g6 22. Qg3
$5) 21. Rg3 Re7 22. Re1 $16 Rbe8 23. Kc1 {[%csl Gc1] Now White's king is safe
whereas Black's queen is stuck on h2.} Ra8 24. f4 {[%cal Rg3h3]} Qh5 25. Rh3
Qg4 26. f5 {1-0 (29) Sokolov,I (2623)-Vazquez Igarza,R (2606) Montpellier FRA
2015}) (8... Ba6 9. Bxa6 Nxa6 10. O-O Re8 (10... c5 11. Qa4 Nc7 12. dxc5 {
Now we shift our focus to Black's hanging pawns.} bxc5 13. Rfd1 Qe7 (13... Qc8
14. a3 Bxc3 15. Bxc3 Ne4 16. Be5 $14 {[%csl Rc5,Rd5][%cal Gf3d2] 1-0 (47)
Chatalbashev,B (2546) -Urkedal,F (2552) Fagernes NOR 2017}) 14. Rac1 Rfd8 15.
a3 Bxc3 16. Bxc3 Ne4 17. Ba5 Rd6 18. Qb3 $16 {1-0 (54) Kovalenko,I (2654)
-Deepan,C (2531) Riga LAT 2019}) 11. Rc1 Bf8 (11... c5 12. Qa4 Nc7 13. dxc5
bxc5 14. Rfd1 a5 15. a3 Qd6 16. Be1 c4 17. Nxd5 Ncxd5 18. axb4 axb4 19. Qb5 $14
{1-0 (44) Sargissian,G (2676)-Pashikian,A (2612) Yerevan ARM 2014}) 12. Ne5 c5
13. f4 cxd4 14. exd4 Nc7 15. f5 $36 {1-0 (30) Salem,A (2675)-Gajewski,G (2626)
Moscow RUS 2019}) 9. O-O Bd6 (9... a6 10. Ne5 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gd1f3,Yd2e1] Now we
have the position we wanted without the inclusion of Rc1. This favours White,
as he can now move the rook to d1 if needed.}) (9... Re8 10. Ne5 {[%cal Gf2f4,
Gd1f3] , with a favourable version for White.}) (9... Nbd7 10. Qc2 $5 (10. Rc1
{[%cal Yc3b5] , transposing to ideas which we saw in earlier chapters.}) 10...
a6 (10... Re8 11. Nb5 Bxd2 12. Nxd2 $14 a6 13. Nxc7 Rc8 14. Nxe8 Rxc2 15. Nxf6+
Nxf6 16. Bxc2 $18 {1/2-1/2 (43) Robert,Y (1774)-Hutois,M (2265) Sautron FRA
2018}) (10... Be7 11. Rad1 $1 {[%csl Gd1][%cal Gd1d8]} c5 12. Ne5 {With a
better position.}) 11. Ne5 c5 (11... Bd6 12. f4 c5 13. Be1 $1 {[%cal Ge1h4]}
Be7 14. Rd1 {[%csl Gd1][%cal Gd1d8] Keeping an eye on the d-file before
