[%csl Gd3][%cal Ga3a4,Ga1b1,Rb1b8,Gc2h7]}) 14. Rae1 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) (9...
Be7 {A flexible move. Black plans to react depending on how White proceeds.}
10. Ne5 (10. Qb1 $5 c5 11. Rd1 (11. dxc5 bxc5 12. e4 {Now the bishop is on e7
instead of d6, which allows Black to push the central pawns.} c4 13. Bc2 d4 $15
{[%cal Gd8d4]}) 11... Nbd7 (11... c4 12. Be2 {[%cal Gb2b3] White will have a
slight edge once he plays b3.}) (11... Nc6 12. dxc5 bxc5 13. e4 {[%csl Gd1]
[%cal Gd1d8]} d4 (13... c4 14. Bf1 d4 15. Bf4 $14 {[%cal Gd1d8,Yb2b3,Yc3d5]})
14. e5 $1 $36) 12. Ne5 {, with a complex position.}) 10... c5 11. Rc1 Nc6 12.
Be1 {[%emt 0:00:04] transposes to chapter 4.}) 10. Qb1 $5 {[%cal Gb1h7,Gb2b4]
This was the main point of not committing to Rc1. White wants to expand
quickly on the queenside by playing b4, a4 etc.} Re8 (10... Nbd7 11. b4 a6 12.
a4 c6 13. Rc1 Re8 14. e4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 Bf8 16. a5 g6 17. Bg5 $14 {1/2-1/2 (43)
