1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd2 d5 6. Nf3 c5 7. a3 Bxc3 (7...
cxd4 8. axb4 dxc3 9. Bxc3 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 Bd7 12. Ke2 Rc8 13. Ne5
(13. Bd3 Nd5 14. Ne5 Be8 15. Bd2 f6 16. Nc4 Rd8 17. Rhc1 Nc6 $11 {1-0 (40)
Karjakin,S (2763)-So,W (2799) Berlin GER 2018}) 13... Be8 14. f3 $14) 8. Bxc3
Ne4 (8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Ne4 (9... Re8 10. Be2 Ne4 11. Rc1 dxc4 12. O-O a6 13.
Bxc4 Nxc3 14. Rxc3 $14 {, with play similar to the mainline, but here Black
has played Re8, which doesn't do much: 1-0 (33) Sandipan, C (2555)-Shyam, N 
(2448) Jammu IND 2018}) 10. Rc1 Nxc3 11. Rxc3 {transposes.}) 9. Rc1 Nxc3 10.
Rxc3 cxd4 11. Nxd4 {Though objectively the position is equal, practically
White can pose as many problems as he wants during the game. It is clear that
Black is fighting for a draw, as White is pushing in most endings that can
arise.} ({90 years ago, Alekhine, true to his style, chose the most dynamic
approach by playing with an IQP.} 11. exd4 $5 Nc6 12. Be2 dxc4 13. Bxc4 Qf6 14.
O-O Rd8 15. Rd3 {1-0 (39) Alekhine,A-Kmoch,H San Remo 1930}) 11... dxc4 (11...
b6 $6 {Unnecessarily weakening the c6-square.} 12. cxd5 Qxd5 13. Be2 Bb7 14.
Bf3 Qd7 15. O-O Na6 16. Bc6 (16. Nc6 {is also possible.}) 16... Bxc6 17. Nxc6
Qb7 18. b4 $16 {[%csl Ra6] 1-0 (50) Salemgareev,T (2375)-Chukavin,K (2291)
Riga LAT 2018}) (11... e5 12. Nb3 dxc4 13. Bxc4 Qxd1+ 14. Kxd1 Nd7 15. Na5 $1 {
[%csl Ra7,Rb7]} Nf6 16. Ke2 $14 {1-0 (38) Sengupta,D (2565)-Reuker,J (2377)
Pardubice CZE 2018}) (11... Nc6 12. cxd5 Qxd5 (12... Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Qxd5 14.
Qxd5 exd5 15. Be2 $14 {[%cal Ge2f3,Rh1a8]}) 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Qc2 {[%csl Gc3]
[%cal Rc1c6] White has risk-free play here due to the weak c-pawn and his firm
control over the dark squares.} h6 (14... Rb8 15. b4 $1 {White takes control
of all the squares on the queenside.} Qg5 16. Rc5 Qf6 17. Qc1 Qg6 18. f3 Rd8
19. Kf2 Bb7 20. Be2 Qh6 21. h4 Rd7 22. g3 Rbd8 23. Rd1 Rxd1 24. Bxd1 $16 {
1-0 (47) Bluebaum,M (2610)-Raja,H (2432) Karlsruhe GER 2019}) 15. f3 a5 16. Bc4
Qe5 17. f4 Qf6 18. O-O Ba6 19. Rf2 $1 {[%cal Gf2b2] Defending the second rank.}
Rfd8 (19... Bxc4 20. Rxc4 {It is not a pleasant task to defend such a position.
}) 20. h3 {Creating a safe haven for the king.} Rd6 21. Ba2 Rc8 22. f5 $1 $16 {
[%cal Ga2g8] 1-0 (47) Nihal, S (2618)-Saduakassova, D (2519) Wijk aan Zee NED
2020}) (11... a6 $5 {Black is using a waiting strategy.} 12. Nb3 {As usual we
transfer our knight to the queenside.} dxc4 (12... Nc6 {unnecessarily leaves
Black with an IQP after} 13. cxd5 $14) 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Bxc4 {[%cal Gb3a5]} b6
(14... Nd7 15. Be2 $1 $14 {[%cal Ye2f3]}) 15. f3 $1 {Aimed against Black's
light-squared bishop.} Bb7 16. Kf2 Nd7 17. Rhc1 Rac8 {White should have
exerted more pressure by playing} 18. h4 $14 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5] Playing on
both sides of the board is the key idea in such positions. Here we expand on
the queenside and in the process we try to create one more weakness on the
kingside. Once we have strengthened our position to the maximum, we can
consider exchanging one pair of rooks and keep the other one, to create even
more weaknesses.} (18. Be2 $6 {allowed Black to equalise comfortably after}
Rxc3 19. Rxc3 Rc8 20. Rxc8+ Bxc8 $11 {0-1 (54) Harika,D (2495)-Moiseenko,A 
(2635) Douglas ENG 2019}) (18. g4 {Also possible with the same intention of
expanding on the kingside.})) 12. Bxc4 Bd7 (12... a6 13. O-O b5 14. Be2 Bb7 15.
Bf3 {Exchanging the light-squared bishop, so that the knight on d4 can jump to
c6 at any time.} Ra7 16. Bxb7 Rxb7 17. Qf3 Rd7 18. h3 g6 19. Qg3 $16 {Black's
knight is stuck on b8 to stop White from invading via c6.1/2-1/2 (31) Serarols
Mabras, B (2356)-Miezis,N (2486) Stockholm SWE 2019}) (12... e5 13. Nb5 Qxd1+
14. Kxd1 Rd8+ 15. Kc1 Nc6 16. Bd5 $1 {Improving the bishop to the much better
and dominant diagonal.} Ne7 17. Bf3 $14 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Rh1a8] 1/2-1/2 (38)
Lupulescu,C (2601)-Visakh Nr (2489) Sovata ROU 2018}) (12... Nd7 13. Bxe6 fxe6
14. Nxe6 Qe7 15. Nxf8 Nxf8 16. O-O $14 {In praxis it is very difficult for
Black to play such a position, as both minor pieces lack outposts. White won
in 1-0 (83) Zakhartsov, V (2519)-Shuvalova, P (2406) Skolkovo RUS 2019}) 13.
O-O Nc6 {It is clear that White has to avoid the exchange of knights as he has
a space advantage. The interesting question is: Where to play the knight?} 14.
Nb3 {[%cal Yb3c5] I like this move more because White doesn't have any real
attacking chances on the kingside here. From b3, the knight can move to a5 or
c5, to provoke weaknesses in Black's camp.} (14. Nf3 {Also possible. But in my
view White's knight isn't doing much here.}) 14... Ne5 (14... Qe7 15. Be2 $1 {
[%cal Ge2f3] Transferring the bishop to the better diagonal.} Rfc8 16. Qd2 Nd8
17. Nc5 $1 Be8 (17... Rxc5 18. Rxc5 Qxc5 19. Qxd7 $16 {[%cal Ge2f3] The
position is open and the bishop is stronger than the knight.}) 18. Rfc1 $14 {
White has a slight edge as his position is easier to play. 1/2-1/2 (49)
Riazantsev,A (2671)-Inarkiev,E (2709) Doha QAT 2016}) 15. Be2 Bc6 16. Qxd8
Rfxd8 17. Nd4 Bd5 18. Rfc1 {White has control over the c-file. He will be able
to play f3 and a timely e4 or f4, to kick both minor pieces away from the
centre, as was demonstrated beautifully in 1-0 (52) Vitiugov,N (2732)
-Huschenbeth,N (2620) Khanty-Mansiysk RUS 2019} *

