symmetrical pawns, as they favour the side with the bishops.} 11. Qc2 Nbd7 12.
Ne5 (12. O-O-O {There was no need to castle long right away. White could have
kept his opponent guessing about his intentions.} Qc7 {1/2-1/2 (14) Voiska, M 
(2354) -Bojkovic, N (2416) Istanbul TUR 2003}) 12... Nxe5 13. Bxe5 $36 {
Now White can castle however the position demands.}) 11. Qc2 {Stopping Black
from playing Ne4/ Be4} Nbd7 12. O-O a5 (12... Bxf3 {Intending to spoil White's
pawn structure, but this helps White, as he can play Kh1 and Rg1.} 13. gxf3 {
[%csl Gc3,Gd3][%cal Gg1h1,Gf1g1,Gb1h7,Ga1h8]}) (12... h6 13. Rfd1 a5 14. Nd2
Ra6 15. Ne4 Qa8 16. Nxf6+ Nxf6 17. f3 $14 {1/2-1/2 (51) Aleksandrov, A (2589)
-Bartel, M (2609) Bialystok POL 2017}) 13. Rad1 Ra6 {When we keep checking our
lines with the computer, we tend to fail to assess the practical aspects of
the position. That is why I recommend studying the classics, to understand
piece placement, which pieces to exchange and which ones to keep, etc.} 14. Ng5
$1 {Yusupov comes up with a subtle plan.} h6 15. Ne4 {White voluntarily gets
rid of his bishop pair, as his remaining dark-squared bishop is stronger than
the knight.} Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Bxe4 17. Qxe4 {White has a target (the d6-pawn)
whereas Black's position is solid yet without counterplay. This gives White
very pleasant play.} a4 18. Rd2 $14 {White's bishop on c3 does a multi-purpose
job, as it protects the queenside and also keeps an eye on Black's kingside.
White has easy play whereas Black has to be precise to maintain the balance.
Black fought hard and drew the game in 1/2-1/2 (41) Jussupow,A (2655)-Salov,V 
(2655) Linares 1992}) 10. exd4 d5 11. b3 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4]} Nbd7 (11... dxc4 12.
bxc4 Be4 13. O-O {White yet again is willing to give up the bishop pair.} Nbd7
